1. "A network drive you can attach to your instances while they run"
      It is not a physical hard drive inside your computer
      It is a storage drive connected over the network to your EC2 instance
      Just like how you connect an external hard drive to your laptop — but over the internet
      You can attach and detach it from EC2 instances anytime

2. "It allows your instances to persist data, even after their termination"
      Normally when you stop or terminate an EC2 instance, all data is lost
      But with EBS, your data is saved even after the EC2 instance is terminated
      Example: Your database files, application logs, configurations — all remain safe

3. "They can only be mounted to one instance at a time"
      One EBS volume can only be attached to one EC2 instance at a time
      You cannot attach the same EBS volume to two EC2 instances simultaneously
      (Note: This is at the CCP/basic level — advanced multi-attach exists for specific volume types)

4. "They are bound to a specific Availability Zone"
    An EBS volume created in us-east-1a can only be attached to an EC2 instance in us-east-1a
    It cannot be directly attached to an instance in us-east-1b
    To move it, you need to create a snapshot first

5. Analogy — "Think of them as a network USB stick"
      Just like a USB stick:
      You can plug it in (attach to EC2)
      Save data on it
      Unplug it (detach from EC2)
      Plug into another computer (attach to another EC2 instance)
      But instead of physically plugging it in, it connects over the network
